<subSubSection id="E59D23E293A7549B8C3ECD600E344130" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="21F38B50D334ACDF330447BC2C7FE52D" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0F574E10D64C7CBF1AD1394CEC5C648B" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
The subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="7FD626EE7CE91CB2B5AC02C9D08E97A3" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Poliandrena)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Poliandrena">Poliandrena</taxonomicName>
Warncke, 1968 is 
<taxonomicName id="A5B1605EFF4268E12A799A05C60DF2F6" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="currently" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="currently">currently</taxonomicName>
unsatisfactorily defined (females keying out in three places in 
<bibRefCitation id="E2C549A1013AB93CDB6D4DED0869164A" author="Warncke, K" journalOrPublisher="Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 110" refId="B47" refString="Warncke, K, 1968a. Die Untergattungen der westpalaearktischen Bienengattung Andrena F. Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra 307: 1 - 110" title="Die Untergattungen der westpalaearktischen Bienengattung Andrena F." volume="307" year="1968 a">
<normalizedToken id="45D4E346EBCE270240D2396DF2F0D9E0" originalValue="Warncke’s">Warncke's</normalizedToken>
1968a
</bibRefCitation>
key) and will probably be broken up in the future as it has been shown to be strongly polyphyletic (
<bibRefCitation id="FEB5B6ED917919DB71528FC071BF776F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" author="Pisanty, G" journalOrPublisher="Gounouilhou, Bordeaux" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B28" refString="Pisanty, G, Richter, R, Martin, T, Dettman, J, Cardinal, S, 2020. Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of andrenine bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). bioRxiv. https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" title="Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of andrenine bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). bioRxiv." url="https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" year="2020">Pisanty et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). It predominantly contains Mediterranean species that have heads that are short and broad (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9CC2DD0CCE837DF5A8B68478A23D9D01" captionStart="Figures 83–86" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 83 - 86. Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps sp. nov. 83 female profile 84 female head 85 female dorsum 86 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">84</figureCitation>
), short facial foveae, strongly punctate metasomas (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FF2BBA7E1E15E5B284AC6014C3E8F76D" captionStart="Figures 83–86" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 83 - 86. Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps sp. nov. 83 female profile 84 female head 85 female dorsum 86 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">86</figureCitation>
), and often show a propodeal triangle that is defined by an external carina and internal rugosity (but not honeycomb-areolate, 
<bibRefCitation id="9C4817E5EF50BB24563AD0DAE22C76D3" author="Warncke, K" journalOrPublisher="Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 110" refId="B47" refString="Warncke, K, 1968a. Die Untergattungen der westpalaearktischen Bienengattung Andrena F. Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra 307: 1 - 110" title="Die Untergattungen der westpalaearktischen Bienengattung Andrena F." volume="307" year="1968 a">Warncke 1968a</bibRefCitation>
). As such, members of the 
<taxonomicName id="C56143F08F3A77C99055B46EBC0C1793" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Poliandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poliandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63702BCCF8C462DF2728FAD7ABA74BA2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Poliandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are often recognised by their similarity to each other rather than by a single character 
<emphasis id="20F1F0D3A0333959DCC9A9C2137077C3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">per se</emphasis>
, in other words a wastebasket taxon.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3C8080FA1ADA6913AD7DC71B51A3ED8E" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName id="1785A29E64C12545AE39BBCD9738BCBD" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena breviceps" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviceps">
<emphasis id="5C135E6DE691B4CAECE64AC6EC769EF0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Andrena breviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is small relative to the rest of the 
<taxonomicName id="20BF9A38929C8B1B114D5293A959AA78" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Poliandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poliandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F898C8579095BF987477FFA5700FB5F1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Poliandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, comparable in size to 
<taxonomicName id="27CFB492A52A497996214F3541A11593" genus="A." lsidName="A. marsae" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="marsae">
<emphasis id="C8DF969EB87FAF46A6DF2AD3D63A4697" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. marsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schmiedeknecht, 1900 and 
<taxonomicName id="42A4AAB6E20A45C6958D2F6EC9C4CD8A" genus="A." lsidName="A. laurivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="laurivora">
<emphasis id="9B4F2C8E1D30C06C18CA081B9ED5DAAF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. laurivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Warncke, 1974, two of the smallest 
<taxonomicName id="01F8BDB179C1A6633383CED0637815D0" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Poliandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poliandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D4A98D844D6400757E82CA3FD937D817" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Poliandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="ED7BFFC26F84DC5E0C004BF1B6C72DB4" genus="A." lsidName="A. breviceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="breviceps">
<emphasis id="722F91D167E82F011DBF7679701F37A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. breviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can easily be separated from them by the colour of the tergites which are dark brown (red in 
<taxonomicName id="DCE978A5FE080DDD69958CEE00E7C459" genus="A." lsidName="A. marsae" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="marsae">
<emphasis id="6056FCB9FB6A045E97FD16AE0CDBC3BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. marsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, dark metallic green-blue in 
<taxonomicName id="58597403882DC69104305D7AEB50EB1D" genus="A." lsidName="A. laurivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="laurivora">
<emphasis id="A6A1033EB9094749EFEFFC44C8DF5848" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. laurivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the sculpturing of the scutum which is shiny and (relatively within the 
<taxonomicName id="301C249157B25C364AAEF2E51B6E54A8" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Poliandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poliandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BA4FCC270943B7F3D62E46CEE603FB13" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Poliandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) sparsely punctate, punctures separated by 2-3 puncture diameters (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5C3B37AD0903151760E94CE40EBD33E6" captionStart="Figures 71–76" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 71 - 76. Andrena (Notandrena) acutidentis sp. nov. 71 male profile 72 male face 73 male gena 74 male dorsum 75 male tergites 76 male genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures71-76" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460653" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">75</figureCitation>
, separated by less than 
<normalizedToken id="8FA5364A63451E85553AF6FC9FCCCE6B" originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
a puncture diameter in 
<taxonomicName id="49187D407B8DF5D5581EE50D64B8258D" genus="A." lsidName="A. marsae" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="marsae">
<emphasis id="5515A0C762AB557607C28035611E1F9D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. marsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and by one puncture diameter in 
<taxonomicName id="B37293A5B7ACB9F68B0D14DFBA0C9391" genus="A." lsidName="A. laurivora" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="laurivora">
<emphasis id="48822D23245FFFC9AE237CF8BA1C3632" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. laurivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, underlying integument shagreened, with a metallic glint). It is also similar to the larger 
<taxonomicName id="5E39DB58D9A9FDD489D2FBD9D4059608" genus="A." lsidName="A. relata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="relata">
<emphasis id="4E6C79133588FAB08C48856DD11B2BFC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. relata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Warncke, 1967 which is newly recorded for Morocco (see below) because of their similar dark tergites and general appearance. However, it can also be separated using the same scutal punctation character (in 
<taxonomicName id="E80FBA55F287F58D33D7E48E0C59271F" genus="A." lsidName="A. relata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="relata">
<emphasis id="56591A62E9D0D1AD78B1480958855C14" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. relata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
punctures dense laterally, centrally separated by at most two puncture diameters) and also by the clypeus where 
<taxonomicName id="0CD2F65FF56B6556FFDF8C23EE329633" genus="A." lsidName="A. breviceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="breviceps">
<emphasis id="CFEC1FF3AADB1CF3A46F149A5C277195" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. breviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a central longitudinal impunctate line that is not present in 
<taxonomicName id="30497B643B58D3AA4758ACD8FB876B20" genus="A." lsidName="A. relata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="relata">
<emphasis id="724C35E1E6C5A75B2F2FE08F5D4FBAAD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. relata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Overall, the shiny and relatively sparsely punctate scutum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="008D82A3C39975518845943883E36CB1" captionStart="Figures 71–76" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 71 - 76. Andrena (Notandrena) acutidentis sp. nov. 71 male profile 72 male face 73 male gena 74 male dorsum 75 male tergites 76 male genitalia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures71-76" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460653" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">75</figureCitation>
) in combination with its small size should allow separation from other 
<taxonomicName id="A914DC03F2B5FD492471367D6A9D97D8" authority="Warncke, 1968" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Poliandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poliandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="85CBFADB6BE5BC7FFE9DF18427765A93" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Poliandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North Africa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8B1CBD2A17CB2CC81CB32106647C592C" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph id="54EBE4294AFA45765A45D21B85A0CB5F" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6327092433708A614A9E0EB196207926" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="1F3D1C83E64843A89CB11954563C0DF3" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Female</emphasis>
: Body length 8.5-9 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AE2CFC0827B45E2DD238E0D1DB8193F3" captionStart="Figures 83–86" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 83 - 86. Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps sp. nov. 83 female profile 84 female head 85 female dorsum 86 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">83</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DB213603EB8AF30FE16AD92EAE806CCC" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Head</emphasis>
: Black, clearly wider than long (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1A9977774A7EB091CE3CB324A4869E39" captionStart="Figures 83–86" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 83 - 86. Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps sp. nov. 83 female profile 84 female head 85 female dorsum 86 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">84</figureCitation>
). Clypeus broad, arched, with large punctures, punctures separated by one puncture diameter except for a central slightly raised impunctate line, underlying surface uneven, slightly but irregularly raised between punctures, shining. Process of labrum broadly trapezoidal, fore margin weakly emarginate. Gena as wide as width of compound eye. Gena, vertex, face, and scape with moderately dense white hairs, longest of these not exceeding length of the scape. Foveae moderately broad, occupying 2/3 of distance between the of compound eye and lateral ocellus, of normal length, not extending below the level of the antennal insertions. Antennae bright, scape and pedicel dark, A3 apically marked with orange, A4-12 predominantly orange, A3 exceeding A4+5, shorter than A4+5+6. Ocelloccipital distance short, 
<normalizedToken id="AD2C207AB0CAAB6488A056F4ACDE2930" originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
width of lateral ocellus. 
<emphasis id="4D19BD8FA80B2E59CF53BE177D3F8A35" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Mesosoma</emphasis>
: Scutum and scutellum moderately punctured, punctures separated by 1-2 puncture diameters, underlying surface shiny, very weakly shagreened laterally and anteriorly (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0A27FE56B24F125751A0A7AD5CC87DAE" captionStart="Figures 83–86" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 83 - 86. Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps sp. nov. 83 female profile 84 female head 85 female dorsum 86 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">85</figureCitation>
). Margins of scutum and scutellum with short, dense whitish hairs, these extending only very sparsely onto the disc. Episternum and propodeum microreticulate, dull, propodeum with weak rugosity, propodeal triangle defined with small but clear slightly raised carina, propodeal triangle with sparse and weak rugosity centrally. Episternum and propodeum with white hairs, longest not exceeding length of the scape. Legs dark, tarsi lightened brown, pubescence whitish to brownish. Femoral and tibial scopa white. Wings hyaline, venation and stigma brown. Nervulus antefurcal. 
<emphasis id="B0CF5E44D2D3A80D8567DF233CCF2114" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Metasoma</emphasis>
: Tergites brownish, margins slightly depressed, lightened white to yellow, apically translucent (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6522B2003B76EEA193EF6227A7B865E3" captionStart="Figures 83–86" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 83 - 86. Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps sp. nov. 83 female profile 84 female head 85 female dorsum 86 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">86</figureCitation>
). Tergites densely, evenly, and finely punctate, punctures separated by one puncture diameter, underlying surface very weakly shagreened, shining. T1 with two small lateral hair patches of white hair on apical margin, T2-4 apically with complete white hair bands obscuring underlying surface. T5-6 with golden hairs flanking pygidial plate. Pygidial plate rounded triangular, flat, without raised margin.
</paragraph>
<caption id="86A9CD0303923611F1EB0A92D590F728" doi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures83-86" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460655" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" start="Figures 83–86" startId="F14">
<paragraph id="C057D15AB2AF3E9CF9956DD567102A6A" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="BF59886EF08DC72B4961BEDBDD3DBE26" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Figures 83-86.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="3651E08BEA758CB004B585D5AE7CBD4E" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviceps" subGenus="Poliandrena">Andrena (Poliandrena) breviceps</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. 
<emphasis id="67B1123082A960EF4B5A7D8EA881E87E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">83</emphasis>
female profile 
<emphasis id="41C25F914EAC1800D3747CC763B735C4" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">84</emphasis>
female head 
<emphasis id="D124F9B0BC7A6BD2EF357EA7E89478B1" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">85</emphasis>
female dorsum 
<emphasis id="2102676EB775CF4D72B13516D3CB9556" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">86</emphasis>
female tergites.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="B42901EF6A1E8B1F84E59E9566D322D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="DA80475EED0B52CE898A703DC439F00D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Male.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="757E05737AEA4FE0181D1EB153834802" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FDCE93AF00D162DD8AD41A031D67BF4B" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F782AF60CF47DE0D7F9F8ED57275DB22" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
The eastern Moroccan desert in the province of 
<normalizedToken id="078E776160A45C3BA8A0651C686FFD6F" originalValue="Drâa-Tafilalet">Draa-Tafilalet</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8589EDDE85CACA2A1C684537979833AA" captionStart="Figure 145" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figure 145. Distribution of sampling locations of newly described species A Andrena hebescens (circles), Andrena semiadesus (squares) B Andrena tenebricorpus (diamond), Andrena niveofacies (circle), Andrena triangulivalvis (triangle) C Andrena sparsipunctata (circles), Andrena breviceps (diamonds) D Andrena acutidentis (squares), Andrena farinosoides (triangles), Andrena nigriclypeus (circle). Relief is indicated by shading, measured in meters above sea level." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figure145" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460665" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">145c</figureCitation>
